Naive player - put a mark in the first empty place in the current row,
then it moves to the next row.

Whatever player - get a random number for each one of the row and the column
then put a mark in the (row,column) (if (row,column) is not empty then get another
 (row,column) by the same method).

Smart player - scans the board column by column, starting from different rows each time.
               It skips columns that contain the opponent’s marks
                and places its mark in the first available cell of a “clean” column.

The advantage of designing the program so that all player classes implement a common interface
 is that it allows the program to treat all players in the same way, regardless of their specific type.
 This design relies on the OOP principles of polymorphism and abstraction.